%C A214986 For x>1, define c(x,0) = 1 and c(x,n) = ceiling(x*c(x,n-1)) for n>0.  Row m of A214986 is the sequence c(r^m,n), where r = golden ratio = (1 + sqrt(5))/2.  The name of the array corresponds to the power ceiling function f(x) = limit of c(x,n)/x^n as n increases without bound; f(x) generalizes the case for x = 3/2 as described under "Power Ceilings" at MathWorld.  For a graph of f(x), see the Mathematica program at A083286.
%C A214986 The term "power ceiling sequence" extends to sequences generated by recurrences P(n) = ceiling(x*P(n-1)) + g(n), and "power ceiling functions" f(x) to the limit of P(n)/x^n in case x>1 and g(n)/x^n -> 0.
%C A214986 Suppose that h is a nonnegative integer and g(n) is a constant.  If x is a positive integer power of the golden ratio r, then f(x), in many cases, lies in the field Q(sqrt(5)).  Examples matching rows of A214986, using g(n) = 0, follow:
%C A214986 ...
%C A214986 x ... P ........ f(x)
%C A214986 r ... A000071 .. (5 + 2*sqrt(5))/2 = 1.8944... (A010532)
%C A214986 r^2 . A001906 .. (5 + 3*sqrt(5))/10 = 1.7082...(A176015)
%C A214986 r^3 . A049652 .. (25 + 11*sqrt(5))/40 = 1.2399...
%C A214986 r^4 . A004187 .. (15 + 7*sqrt(5))/10 = 1.0219...
%C A214986 ...
%C A214986 If k is odd, then f(r^k) = r^k((b(k) + c(k))/d(k)), where
%C A214986 b(k) = L(j)^2 + L(j-1)^2, where j=[(k+1)/2], L=A000032 (Lucas numbers); c(k) = (L(k)+2)*sqrt(5); d(k) = 10*F(k)*L(k), where F=A000045 (Fibonacci numbers).  If k is even, then f(r^k) = r^k/(F(k)*sqrt(5)).
